metadata.name: Magic Board #96
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Giants #57
metadata.description:
Exploring 3D "space" in 2D, a lone Giant sits isolated, his only company are the moons that orbit him and his rings.

Giants vary in color, size, banding, ring makeup, ring thickness and orientation, moons, and the color of the galaxy glowing behind.

The rings vary in color, made up of anywhere between 3 and 45 subrings.

Each planet has a shader gradient, from one color to black, and a perpendicular tint gradient, from one random color to another.

There can be up to 6 moons orbiting the giant, all their own unique colors.

Press 's' in Live View to save a .png

metadata.name: Mado #43
metadata.description:
Windows, viewports, openings into another space. “Mado” is your view into a dimension of ease: Gentle curves caress the landscape. Thin streams of matter open wide to reveal unseen detail, each fiber following its neighbors with its own approach. Three point brackets frame curves into subcompositions and help you to focus on the texture: “What are these fibers made of?”

What can you glimpse through the window, and what is hidden?

metadata.name: A24Z #299
metadata.description:
Every artist and collector feels the joy of both creating and collecting. But if I could share the joy of creating with collectors. And collectors with their family and friends, what may be an additive process of joy is now perhaps exponential. Joy to the power of 26 to be exact. 

In this work I invite my friends and collectors to collaborate with me. Though not in coding, but together in a process of creating narratives and visuals. Code and story. We didn’t use github, just a simple p5.js editor to try out different programs and palettes. Pedrofe and J0rdan pick their palettes tastefully and carefully. okeoke, perhaps more of a genius than he lets on, picks his palettes blind. No hex color picker. Just straight up rhymes.  

In our discussions verbal language was forbidden. Only emojis were allowed to express our tastes and views. Each emojis put down on google doc was taken with absolutely seriousness. 

Pedro: Loves to taking his daily walks on “Magic Mushroom Mountain”

J0rdan: Wonders about “Quark Question Quiches”

Okeoke: Just get lost in “Finnegans’ Flower Fields.”

It has been a great joy to present our illustration book A24Z, 8 more than you know who. Each page expresses the alphabet with the best of our knowledge in semantics and sarcasm. Collect just 1 page, collect the alphabets that spell out your name, collect the whole A to Z. Read it to your children or loved ones. Though you might need to interpolate or extrapolate with great imagination which children all have. But most importantly, like all children, have fun!

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. Preview images are compressed or broken, test capture at 300 sec.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Sketching #121
metadata.description:
Rules : 
  1. Start with either a line or a circle from a number of random points in the space.
  2. A line can only spawn a circle at the end. 
  3. A circle can spawn both lines and circles before it completes the full circle.
  4. A circle can sometimes spawn an inner circle.
  5. Smaller elements will spawn randomly along with the lines.

This was inspired by the patterns in Marvel's movie : Eternals. I enjoyed the line growing animation with basic geometry ( line and circle ). Combining this with the rules It generates interesting results.

To add more variety to the rendering, I've added the dash lines in instead of only solid lines. Also the 'lines' consist of thousands of small dots to give it randomness and a bit of texture feeling.
